<div id="review_152619740" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/152619740" />
    <a title="Juan Valdivia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1955701-juan-valdivia"><img alt="Juan Valdivia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459231376p2/1955701.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/152619740?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Juan Valdivia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Juan Valdivia" href="/user/show/1955701-juan-valdivia">Juan Valdivia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer152619740" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13457876429927635554">For the life of me, I can&apos;t fathom how this book became a bestseller. I made it to page 29 before I closed it and reprieved myself of this book—and I feel like making it to page 29 was an accomplishment. I tried to give this book a chance. I really did, but my god, the prose just slayed me (in a horrific way). Here&apos;s a few choice samples:<br/><br/>&quot;Somehow she sleeps, or approximates it, through the bad hour and into another mirror-world morning.<br/><br/>Walking to an inner flash of metallic migraine light, as if </span>
  <span id="freeText13457876429927635554" style="display:none">For the life of me, I can't fathom how this book became a bestseller. I made it to page 29 before I closed it and reprieved myself of this book—and I feel like making it to page 29 was an accomplishment. I tried to give this book a chance. I really did, but my god, the prose just slayed me (in a horrific way). Here's a few choice samples:<br /><br />"Somehow she sleeps, or approximates it, through the bad hour and into another mirror-world morning.<br /><br />Walking to an inner flash of metallic migraine light, as if reflected off wings of receding dream."<br /><br />Or: "Corridor metaphysics. She wants coffee." <br /><br />But what really killed me, and what really dragged this read was all the excessive details. Page 26 to half of page 28 describes the protagonist waking up, showering and dressing, and catching a cab. Unless I'm Knucklehead of the Year, there was nothing crucial about this sequence, and yet, so much space was lavished in describing it. From what I read, the book has a monsoon of tiny details—and I have no fucking idea what their purpose is, or what they contribute to the narrative. <br /><br />I can't imagine finishing this 367-page book with small font. That would be akin to making Manuel Noriega listening to Guns N' Roses.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13457876429927635554" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


